AsyncFS: Metadata Updates Made Asynchronous for Distributed Filesystems with
In-Network Coordination
Jingwei Xu, Mingkai Dong, Qiulin Tian, Ziyi Tian, Tong Xin, and Haibo Chen
Institute of Parallel and Distributed Systems (IPADS), Shanghai Jiao Tong University
Abstract
Distributed lesystems typically employ synchronous meta-
data updates, facing inherent challenges for access efciency,
load balancing, and directory contention, especially under
dynamic and skewed workloads. This paper argues that syn-
chronous updates are overly conservative for distributed
lesystems. We propose AsyncFS with asynchronous meta-
data updates, allowing operations to return early and defer
directory updates until respective read to enable latency hid-
ing and conict resolution. The key challenge is efciently
maintaining the synchronous semantics of metadata updates.
To address this, AsyncFS is co-designed with a programmable
switch, leveraging the constrained on-switch resources to
holistically track directory states in the network with neg-
ligible cost. This allows AsyncFS to timely aggregate and
efciently apply delayed updates using batching and consoli-
dation before directory reads. Evaluation shows that AsyncFS
achieves up to 13.34
and 3.85
higher throughput, and
61.6% and 57.3% lower latency than two state-of-the-art dis-
tributed lesystems, InniFS and CFS-KV, respectively, on
skewed workloads. For real-world workloads, AsyncFS im-
proves end-to-end throughput by 21.1
, 1.1
and 30.1% over
Ceph, IndexFS and CFS-KV, respectively.
1 Introduction
Two decades ago, when GFS [10] and HDFS [61] origins,
distributed lesystems (DFSs) were designed for large data
access. However, as data center workloads evolves over time,
metadata operation is becoming the performance dominator.
First, the scale of DFS instance is growing, typically storing
hundreds of billions of les and serving hundreds of thou-
sand of tenants [2, 34, 42, 47, 55, 69]. The huge le number
and massive concurrent metadata access heavily stress meta-
data storage and performance [42]. Second, many critical
workloads involve numerous small les [2, 42, 55, 69, 69] and
metadata operations constitute the majority of lesystem op-
erations [35,68,69]. For example, in nine representative work-
loads from Baidu AI Cloud, metadata operations account for
67% to 96% of all lesystem requests for applications rang-
ing from social networks to machine learning [69]. Finally,
highly parallelized storage array [34,47, 69, 70] and advanced
storage media [18, 19] makes data access scalable and fast,
making data operations less likely to be the bottleneck.
A series of studies [29,35,42,44,47,50,51,53,55,66,69,70]
have been made on scaling DFS metadata performance, yet
there are still challenges remaining. First, while it is typical to
partition the directory tree across multiple metadata servers
to scale out, the selection of partitioning granularity involves
an inherent trade-off between load balance and operation
overhead, hard to achieve both [43]. Coarse-grained partition-
ing [12, 42, 44, 47, 55,70] groups le inodes with their parent
directory. In this approach, large directories can easily become
hotspots, especially in skewed workloads [2,68]. In contrast,
ne-grained partitioning [11, 35, 69] evenly shufes le in-
odes across metadata servers. This approach achieves good
load balance, but breaks the colocation between inodes and
parent directories. In consequence, metadata operations need
to use costly distributed transactions to consistently update
metadata partitioned to different nodes, which can be avoided
in coarse-grained partitioning. Second, state-of-the-art dis-
tributed metadata services often suffer from contention on
directory metadata. Parent-related operations (e.g. mkdir and
create) are serialized over parent directory metadata, resulting
in suboptimal performance and hindering scalability [13, 69].
A fundamental reason for the aforementioned challenges
is the use of synchronous metadata updates. As lesystem
semantics require visibility (the effect of an operation are
visible to subsequent operations) and atomicity (no partial
updates are observable), state-of-the-art DFSs typically use
transactions to synchronously update involved metadata ob-
jects before operation returns. Unfortunately, this approach
exposes the cross-server coordination overhead and metadata
contention on the critical path, leading to high operation la-
tency and performance bottlenecks.
In this paper, we argue that synchronous updates are overly
conservative for DFSs, based on the observation that a di-
rectory is typically not immediately read after being updated
in representative data center workloads, and propose asyn-
1
arXiv:2410.08618v1 [cs.DC] 11 Oct 2024
chronous updates. The intuition of asynchronous updates is
to allow operations return early and defer directory updates
until respective read, allowing for latency hiding and conict
resolution. However, as we want to preserve the visibility of
metadata updates, a mechanism is required to register un-
nalized directory updates and notify directory reads. If we
implement the mechanism on a server, it introduces additional
RTT and can become throughput bottleneck, as it lay on-path
of every directory-related operations. Fortunately, we nd that
programmable switches are naturally positioned in the critical
path of each metadata access and can manipulate packets of
a whole cluster with line-rate. Thus, they are well-suited for
the central management in the asynchronous update protocol.
Based on these insights, we present AsyncFS, an asyn-
chronous distributed lesystem co-designed with a pro-
grammable switch for conict coordination. AsyncFS is built
for POSIX APIs and semantics, and achieves good load bal-
ance, low latency, high scalability under skewed workloads.
First, we propose an efcient protocol for asynchronous
metadata updates using metadata scattering and aggregation,
offering the following benets: (a) it enables most metadata
operations to be completed in one round-trip time (RTT) while
using ne-grained partitioning for load balance, breaking the
trade-off made by previous DFSs; (b) it allows merging con-
tending metadata updates before applying them, alleviating
metadata contention. Specically, when an operation updates
objects on multiple servers (typically an object and its parent
directory), AsyncFS logs the directory update on the server
hosting the object and mark the directory as scattered in the
programmable switch. When reading a directory, the switch
indicates if the directory is scattered. If so, AsyncFS aggre-
gates postponed updates from other servers before accessing
the directory. To further expedite the aggregation process and
reduce contention on directory metadata, AsyncFS consoli-
dates updates to the same directory before aggregation, lever-
aging the commutative property of metadata updates [30, 69].
Second, we co-design AsyncFS with a programmable
switch to efciently track directory scattering within the net-
work. Our insight is that, due to its powerful packet process-
ing capabilities and central position in the network, the pro-
grammable switch serves as a superior coordinator compared
to regular servers. Given the constrained on-switch memory
and computing resources, we use a compact in-network stale
set with high utilization and low conict rate by organizing
the switch registers in a set-associative manner. By inspect-
ing specic headers in packets, the the state set can insert,
query, and remove a directorys ngerprint at line rate and
redirect packets as needed. Consequently, AsyncFS can query
or update directory states at negligible latency overhead.
Evaluation shows that AsyncFS achieves up to 13.34
higher throughput over InniFS [42] under skewed work-
loads, and 57.3% lower latency than CFS-KV [69], two state-
of-the-art distributed le systems.For real-world workloads,
AsyncFS speedups end-to-end throughput by 21.1

2 Background and Motivation
2.1 Characteristics of Datacenter Workloads
A directory is typically not immediately read after be-
ing updated. Table 1 presents the ratio of metadata opera-
tions in three deployed instances of PanguFS in Alibaba [42],
which supports various services like data processing, ob-
ject storage, and block storage. According to the table, op-
erations that update directories (i.e., create, delete, mkdir,
rmdir, and rename) account for 30.76% of metadata oper-
ations, while operations that read directories (i.e., readdir
and statidr) account for only 4.19%. According to the pi-
geonhole principle, the difference in ratios indicates that over
(30.76% 4.19%)/30.76% = 86.3%
of the directory updates
satisfy (a) the updated directory is never read after this oper-
ation or (b) the updated directory is updated by at least one
another operation before being read. In both cases, the direc-
tory update is not immediately followed by directory reads,
and asynchronously applying directory updates helps hide
latency and reduce contention.
Datacenter workloads are skewed in multiple dimensions.
These skewed access patterns pose signicant challenges to
metadata management of modern DFSs.
Unbalanced directory hierarchies. Most directories in dis-
tributed lesystems contain fewer than 128 entries, yet
some directories extend to over a million entries [7, 54, 55].
This high variance results in an unbalanced directory hier-
archy in DFSs, posing challenges for the strategy of storing
a directory across multiple nodes.

Directory hotspots. Besides the unbalanced logical hier-
archy, applications tend to organize related les into di-
rectories. Thus, many les from the same directory may
be accessed in a short time [35, 42, 47], leading to access
hotpots in the directory tree.
Burst operations. Many applications exhibit distinct bound-
aries between computation and storage I/Os, causing oper-
ation bursts on the critical path. For example, compute en-
gines rename a set of les after computation completes [47].
Also, electronic design automation (EDA) programs batch
creations and deletions of temporary les during emulation.
The bursts lead to temporal imbalance.
2.2 Distributed Metadata Partitioning
Distributed lesystems partition the directory tree across a
cluster of metadata servers to scale out metadata storage and
performance [35, 42, 44, 47, 69, 70]. The partition strategy
is an important design choice, which affects operation over-
head and load distribution, greatly inuencing performance
and scalability. We classify existing partition strategies into
two categories by whether coupling les inodes with parent
directories, as depicted in Figure 1 and compared in Table 2.
Parent-children grouping strategies. This category refers
to the strategies that colocate regular les inodes with their
parent directories, e.g., subtree partitioning [10, 61] and per-
directory hashing [12, 42, 44, 47, 55], as illustrated in Fig-
ure 1(a). Previous studies adopt this category of strategies
since it achieves good metadata locality that reduces opera-
tion overhead. Specically, metadata operations often simul-
taneously update metadata objects with their parent directo-
ries metadata, e.g., le create. With parent-children grouped,
these operations can be completed on a single server, avoid-
ing expensive cross-server coordination. The downside of this
approach is that it gathers inodes of les in the same direc-
tory to the same server, resulting in potential bottlenecks that
undermines scalability under skewed workload.
Parent-children separating strategies. This kind of strat-
egy distributes le inodes independently, regardless of the lo-
cation of their parent directories, e.g., per-le hashing [11,69],
as illustrated in Figure 1(b). By evenly distributing metadata
objects, parent-children separating strategies achieve good
load balance over le inode access. However, metadata op-
erations may suffer expensive cross-server coordination to
consistently update multiple metadata objects.

2.3 Challenges
Modern datacenters demand distributed metadata service with
high scalability, high throughput and low latency. However,
there are several challenges in the design.
Challenge 1: There is an inherent trade-off between reduc-
ing operation overhead and improving load balance in the
design of directory tree partitioning.
To reduce operation overhead, it is important to colocate
les inodes with parent directory. Metadata operations (e.g.,
create and delete) often update a metadata object together
with its parent directorys metadata. With the objects colo-
cated, the operation can be executed on a single server, avoid-
ing expensive distributed protocols [42].
To improve load balance, it is important to scatter the les
in the same directory. As les in the same directory are often
related to each other and intensively accessed in a short time,
grouping them together makes the lesystem vulnerable to
hotspots [35, 42, 47].
However, colocating les inodes with parent directory
inherently conicts with scattering les in the same directory,
making it difcult to have the best of both worlds.
We perform an evaluation to demonstrate how this trade-
off manifests in performance. We implement InniFS by fol-
lowing its paper [42] and implement CFS-KV by replacing
InniFSs partition strategy (i.e., per-directory hashing) with
that of CFS [69] (i.e., per-le hashing). Figure 2(a) shows
that when performing stat on random les in a shared di-
rectory, CFS-KVs throughput scales linearly for the number
of servers while InniFS suffers scalability bottleneck. Fig-
ure 2(b) shows that CFS-KV suffers higher create latency
3
than InniFS, mainly due to higher network overhead from
cross-server transactions. Notably, InniFS has higher storage
latency because it stores all le inodes on the same server,
reducing the performance of its underlying key-value store.
Challenge 2: Concurrent operations in the same directory
suffer low inter-server and intra-server parallelism for parent
directory contention, hindering performance scaling.
Regardless of the directory tree partitioning strategy, the
contention on directory metadata often becomes the perfor-
mance bottleneck. For example, to create a burst of les in
a single directory, each operation needs to update the times-
tamps and entry list of the parent directory. Although the
creation of the les inodes can be parallelized over multiple
servers (e.g., with parent-children separating partitioning), the
updates of the parent directory are serialized on the server
that stores it, resulting in low inter-server parallelism. Also,
as conventional approaches rely on transactions and locks to
guarantee the atomicity of metadata modications, the server
can hardly leverage multicore parallelism to accelerate direc-
tory updates, resulting in low intra-server parallelism.
As shown in Figure 2(c) and Figure 2(d), both lesystems
throughput of create hardly scales with regard to the number
of servers and the number of cores per server. It indicates that
both inter-server and intra-server parallelism are bottlenecked
by the contention on the parent directory.
2.4 Programmable Switch
Programmable switch is a packet switching device equiped
with programmable ASICs and stateful memory [1, 17, 45]. It
can do user-customized manipulation on packets while for-
warding them with extremely high speed. Compared with ma-
nipulating packets with a standard server, the programmable
switch have two advantages: (a) Sitting on the center of the
network, the programmable switch naturally has a global view
of all the communications. (b) The ASIC-based hardware pro-
cesses packets at line-rate, providing much higher throughput
and lower latency than standard servers. We justify these
statements with evaluation in 6.5.2.
3 Overview
To break the inherent limitations discussed in 2.3, AsyncFS
adopts network-codesigned asynchronous execution of meta-
data operations to promote parallelism and hides latency.
Design goals. AsyncFS is a POSIX distributed lesystem
designed to meet the following goals: (a) high throughput
under skewed workload; (b) one-RTT latency for most opera-
tions; (c) stable performance under operation bursts.
3.1 Design Rationale
Key idea: asynchronous directory updates. Our key idea
is to leverage asynchronous updates to hide cross-server over-
head and exploit parallelism for metadata operations. POSIX
metadata operations, except for rename, update no more than

its parent directory [13]; thus, by logging and delaying the
update to the remote parent directory, AsyncFS can locally ex-

overhead and allows contended metadata updates of parent

Key enabler: programmable switch. To ensure the de-

AsyncFS adopts the programmable switch, which is naturally
a centralized device, to monitor directory states with line-rate
and sub-RTT latency.
However, as the on-chip memory and computing resources
are limited, it is non-trivial to maintain all directory states of
a whole lesystem. We observe that, though the total num-
ber of directories can be huge, the set of directories whose
metadata has been modied in a given duration is small. For
example, for a lesystem that can create/delete 1 million les
per second, the maximun number of directories modied per
100 milliseconds is 100 thousand, which is small enough to t
into the switch data plane. Therefore, by periodically apply-
ing delayed updates to corresponding directories and ushing
on-switch data structure, on-switch state tracking is possible.
3.2 Overall Architecture
As depicted in Figure 4, AsyncFS consists of three compo-
nents: clients, metadata servers, and a programmable switch.
Clients. AsyncFS provides a user-space library (LibFS)
for each client to communicate with servers. Like previous
studies [35, 42, 55], the client maintains a metadata cache to
accelerate path resolution. The cache, along with the server-
side invalidation list, is also used to determine the existence
of the parent directory for one-RTT multi-inode operations.
Metadata servers. In AsyncFS, metadata objects are dis-
tributed ne-grainedly across metadata servers. Each server
uses a key-value store (i.e. RocksDB [56]) for metadata stor-
age. The per-directory change-logs track postponed modi-
cations to remote directories. The invalidation list tracks
recently deleted directories for path validity checking. The
server uses a write-ahead log (WAL) for crash recovery.
In-network stale set. The stale set tracks stale directories,
i.e., directories with delayed updates stored on other servers.
The programmable switch monitors AsyncFSs trafc and
queries or updates the stale set accordingly.

3.3 Metadata Scheme
Table 3 presents the metadata scheme of AsyncFS. Each
directory has a 256-bit id that is uniquely and permanently
assigned on directory creation. Metadata objects are stored
as key-value pairs, where the key is the concatenation of the
parent directorys id (i.e. pid) and the le/directory name, and
the value is the corresponding metadata.
AsyncFS adopts parent-children separating strategy for
load balance, partitioning le/directory metadata (i.e. inodes)
by hashing (pid, name). A directorys entry list is stored as
multiple Dir Entry key-value pairs, which are always stored
on the same server as the directory.
Though not shown in the table, AsyncFS generates a 49-
bit ngerprint for each directory by hashing (pid, directory
name). The ngerprint is mainly used by the switch and thus
is shorter to accommodate the switchs limited register width.
Multiple directories may have the same ngerprint. AsyncFS
guarantees that all directories with the same ngerprint (i.e.,
a ngerprint group) are partitioned to the same server to
simplify conict handling.
4 AsyncFS Design
4.1 Directory State and Transition
State denition. In AsyncFS, each directory is in one of the
two states: normal state, indicating that all returned updates to
the directory have been applied to its inode, or scattered state,
indicating that there are not-yet-applied updates in change-
logs. Directory states are tracked by the in-network stale set,
and metadata operations can query or modify directory states.
State transition. Figure 3 shows the transitions of directory
states. A directory is created in normal state. In normal state,
directory reads can directly access the inode. When AsyncFS
performs an asynchronous update to the directory, the di-
rectory is turned into scattered state, with delayed updates
scattered on other servers. When AsyncFS reads a directory
in scattered state, it aggregates related delayed updates from
all servers and applies them to the directories inodes, turning
it into normal state.
Transition granularity. Since the switch identies directo-
ries by ngerprints, the granularity of state transition is n-
gerprint group, i.e., all directories with the same ngerprint.
Thus, a metadata aggregation will aggregate all directories
in the target ngerprint group. This does not complicate ag-
greagation as AsyncFS partitions directories with the same
ngerprint to the same server.

4.2 Asynchronous Metadata Operations
Metadata operations can be classied into three categories
according to the number of inodes they access [13], and
AsyncFS handles them differently.
Single-inode operations, including open, close, read, write,
stat, statdir and readdir, access the inode of the target ob-
ject. AsyncFS achieves load balance for these operations
since AsyncFS uniformly distributed metadata objects. Di-
rectory reads, including statdir and readdir, initiate a meta-
data aggregation before reading scattered directory inodes.
Double-inode operations, including create, delete, mkdir,
rmdir, access inodes of the target object and its parent di-
rectory. Double-inode operations are handled on the server
storing the target object. Updates to the parent directory are
performed asynchronously to hide cross-server overhead.
Rename is the most complex metadata operation that up-
dates up to four inodes. AsyncFS guarantees rename con-
sistency with distributed transactions and avoids orphaned
loops with a centralized rename coordinator [42,69]. No-
tably, if the source is a directory, AsyncFS initiates an
aggregation to apply all delayed updates before rename.
Generally, each metadata operation consists of six phases:
path resolution, locking involved objects, checking whether
the operation can succeed, logging into persistent storage,
modifying involved objects, and nally unlocking. We intro-
duce the detailed workow of double-inode operations and
directory reads in the rest of this subsection.
4.2.1 Workow of mkdir, create and delete.
The green circles and lines in Figure 4 illustrate the workow
of mkdir, create and delete. Take creating le A as an example.
First, AsyncFS adopts client-side path resolution with server-
5
side validation check [42]. The client performs permission
checks along the path by querying its local metadata cache
(
). On cache misses, the client sends a lookup request to
fetch the id and permission of the path component. After the
client-side resolution, the client sends the request to the owner
server of A, which is determined by hashing As pid and name,
where the freshness of the client-side cache is examined later
to avoid stale checking.
After receiving the request, the server does the following
work. First, the server locks potentially modied objects in
the operation, including (2a) the read lock of the change-log
As parent directory and (2b) the write lock of As inode in
the key-value store. Second, the server does necessary checks,
including (3a) server-side validation check: whether any path
component of A is in the invalidation list, and (3b) whether
le A already exists. If the validation check fails, the server
denies the request so that the client will invalidate the corre-
sponding metadata cache entries and re-fetch the metadata. If
both checks are passed, the operation can succeed and is per-
sistently logged in the write-ahead log (
). Then, the server
modies local objects, including (5a) records the creation of
A along with the timestamp in the change-log, and (5b) inserts
As inode into its local key-value store. Finally, the server
sends a response to the client through the switch. The switch
parses the response packet and inserts the parents ngerprint
into the stale set (
). If the insertion succeeds, the switch
multicasts the packet to (7a) the client, notifying the complet-
ing of the operation and (7b) the server that performed the
operation, notifying the server to unlock the objects. If the in-
sertion fails (e.g., due to overow), the operation fallbacks to
synchronous metadata update, where the switch forwards the
packet to the parent directorys owner serve and updates to the
parent directory are applied immediately and synchronously.
4.2.2 Workow of statdir and readdir.
Reading a scattered directory may trigger metadata aggrega-
tion in AsyncFS. The workow is illustrated by the orange
circles and lines in Figure 4. When the switch gets a request
packet for directory read, it queries the stale set to determine
the state of the requested directory (
) and attaches the state
to the packet. When the server receives the packet, it rst
acquires read lock of the directory inode (
) and checks (3a)
path validation and (3b) inode existence like operations dis-
cussed above. Then, the server checks the state of the request
directory. If the directory is in normal state, the server directly
responds to the client according to the directorys inode. Oth-
erwise, the server issues a metadata aggregation to renew the
directorys inode before replying to the client.
To aggregate a directory A, the owner server (i.e., the ag-
gregator) rst blocks statdir and readdir to all directories in

4.3 Change-Log Recast and Applying
Asynchronous metadata updates allows parallel and local log-
ging of directory updates, deferring contention on the parent
directories. AsyncFS further parallelly mitigates directory
contention by recasting the change-logs before applying them
to the parent directory inode. Next, we will present the change-
log design and how we recast and apply the change-logs.
Each AsyncFS server maintains a local change-log for ev-
ery scattered directory. As depicted in Figure 6, each change-
log entry represents a delayed parent directory update, con-
sisting of the timestamp, the operation type (create, delete,
etc.), and the lename.
Recast. To further reduce directory contention, AsyncFS
recasts the change-log entries by leveraging the commuta-
6
tive and associative properties of metadata updates [30, 69].
Specically, as the new mtime of a directory is the timestamp
of the last update, AsyncFS consolidates the timestamps of
entries and keeps only the maximal timestamp. The opera-
tion type and the lename are then stored in an operation
queue. The consolidation of timestamps in advance reduces
contention on the directory inode.
Upon receiving an aggregation request, the server transmits
the requested change-log to the server owning the correspond-
ing directory (i.e., the owner server). After receiving each
change-log, the owner server will go through the operation
queue and update the directory entry list using the key-value
stores put() and delete() accordingly. Finally, the owner server
employs a local transaction to update inode metadata (e.g.,
timestamps and size) atomically. Note that it is safe to update
the directory entry list outside of the transaction, as directory
reads are blocked during the aggregation and cannot observe
the transient inconsistency.
AsyncFS mitigates the contention of parent directory up-
dates in two-fold. Asynchronous metadata updates enable
all servers to handle updates to remote parent directories
locally in the change-logs, which increases inter-server paral-
lelism. On the other hand, the change-log recast consolidates
timestamps beforehand to minimize updates to the directorys
inode, facilitating the parallel processing of directory entry
list operations and improving the intra-server parallelism.
Proactive aggregation. To prevent prolonged aggregation
stalls for the rst directory read after a series of asynchronous
directory updates, servers proactively push a change-log to the
directorys server in two conditions: (1) when the change-log
is large enough to ll a maximum transmission unit (MTU);
(2) when the change-log has not been appended for a specic
duration. Upon receiving a change-log push, the directorys
server waits for a grace period during which no further change-
log push is received and then proactively initiates a metadata
aggregation. The grace period prevents premature aggrega-
tion with numerous in-ight directory modications. Such a
proactive aggregation clears the directory state in the switch,
enabling faster subsequent access to the directory without
necessitating the aggregation in the critical path.
4.4 Fault Tolerance
4.4.1 Unreliable network.
AsyncFS protocol is implemented on top of UDP, which
may have issues of packet loss, reordering, and duplication.
AsyncFS handles packet loss with timeout and resending. The
reordering of in-ight packets causes no issue, as AsyncFS
does not assume the order of in-ight packets.
Resending causes packet duplication. Since servers can
identify duplicated packets by sequence numbers and avoid
duplicated operations, we mainly discuss the effect on switch
states. The switch serves three kinds of operations, including
query, insert and remove. Query has no side effects and thus
causes no issues. Duplicated inserts may cause unnecessary
aggregations but do not affect correctness. Only duplicated
removes have consistency issues, and only the aggregation
request sent from servers(
in Figure 4) involves remove op-
eration. Servers attach a server-local sequence number to each
remove requests, which increments with each new request and
resend. The switch records the largest received sequence num-
ber from each server, and performs a remove request only if its
sequence number is larger than any previously received from
the sending server. If a remove request is resent, the server
waits untils responses to the last resend arrives. In this way,
all related change-logs are applied during aggregation and no
duplicated remove requests take effect after the aggregation
completes, ensuring consistency.
4.4.2 Crash Recovery
Server failure. AsyncFS servers maintain data structures in
DRAM and use the write-ahead log to recover lost progress
after server failures, as production deployments (e.g. PanguFS
and HDFS) typically do [42]. To recover from failures, the
server rst redoes operations in the WAL to rebuild its lo-
cal key-value store and change-log entries that havent been
marked as applied. Not that we dont need to rebuilt change-
log entries marked applied, as they have been persisted in
the WAL of the corresponding directory inodes server. Then,
the server recovers its invalidation list by cloning that from
other servers.
Switch failure. After a switch failure, all states in the switch
are lost. Instead of recovering these states, AsyncFS initial-
izes an empty stale set in the switch, and noties all servers
to initiate aggregations. Once all aggregations complete, all
change-log entries are sent to and applied by their directory
inodes server. Thus, all directories in AsyncFS become back
to the normal state, which is consistent with the empty stale
set. To avoid consistency issues, all le system operations are
blocked during recovery until the aggregations complete.

In this section, we will introduce the format of AsyncFS pack-

design of the stale set (5.3), respectively.
5.1 AsyncFS Packet Format
AsyncFS utilizes UDP as the transport layer protocol for
lightweight networking. As depicted by Figure 8, the UDP
payload begins with an optional header that encapsulates a
stale set operation, which can be parsed by the switch. Subse-
quently, the payload contains a AsyncFS request or response
for servers to process. AsyncFS reserves two UDP ports for
AsyncFS trafc with and without the stale set operation header
so that the switch can distinguish the trafc easily.

5.2 Data Plane Layout
Figure 7 presents the layout of the data plane, which consists
of the following components.
Parser. The parser parses the packet headers to extract
elds for subsequent processing.
Router. The Router sets the egress port for (a) regular pack-
ets, according to the destination MAC address and (b) packets
with stale set operations, according to the ngerprint.
Stale set. The stale set maintains a set of unique ngerprints.
It supports three kinds of operations, including (1) insert a
ngerprint into the set; (2) query whether a ngerprint is in
the set; (3) remove a ngerprint from the set. When a packet
arrives, the stale set performs the corresponding operation
according to the OP eld in the header and writes the result
in the RET eld. SEQ is a sequence number for recognizing
duplicated remove requests, as discribed in 4.4.1.
Since one switch may have multiple pipes and pipes do
not share states, we place the stale set in the egress pipes and
route packets that operate on the same ngerprint to the same
pipe, according to the prex of the ngerprint. After entering
an egress pipe, a packet can only leave the pipe from ports
connected to it. If the destination port of the packet belongs
to another pipe, the switch uses packet mirroring to redirect
the packet to the correct pipe, as in prior studies [22, 72].
Address rewriter. If a stale set insertion fails due to over-
ow, AsyncFS needs to redirect the packet to servers for
fallback handling. The address rewriter performs this by over-
writing the destination MAC address and egress port.
5.3 In-Network Stale Set
The in-network stale set maintains the set of directories in
scattered states. Since its performance is critical to that of
metadata operations, and its capacity needs to cover the di-
rectory footprint, we have the following design goals. (1)
Support line-rate query, insert and remove of ngerprint. (2)
Maximize the utility of the constrained on-chip memory to
store more elements.
Structure. Due to programming constraints that prevent the
implementation of complex indexing structures using only
registers, AsyncFS organizes 32-bit registers similarly to a
set-associative cache to store ngerprints. As shown in Fig-
ure 8, each stage contains an array of registers, and registers
at the same position across stages can be horizontally grouped
into a set. In our switch conguration, there are ten stages
available for the stale set, with each stage containing 131,072

Stale set operations. The stale set supports three opera-

by performing a sequence of register actions on the registers
indexed by the index. We dene three register actions: (a) reg-
ister query compares the register value with tag and returns
the result; (b) conditional insert writes tag into the register if
the registers original value is zero, and then returns whether
the original value equals zero or tag; (c) conditional remove
overwrites the register with zero if the old value equals tag.
For stale set query, all stages perform register query se-
quentially and the return values are combined with logical
OR operations to be put in the RET eld of the header. For
stale set remove, all stages perform conditional remove se-
quentially. For stale set insert, stages perform conditional
insert one by one until one of them returns true, and the fol-
lowing stages perform conditional remove. The purpose is
to avoid leaving duplicated tags in the set. Figure 9 gives an
example of stale set insert.

as prior studies proposed [67]. (a) Atomicity. Operations in
the same stage are atomic. (b) Ordered execution. For any two

6 Evaluation
6.1 Experimental Setup
Hardware conguration. We conduct experiments with
eight server machines and three client machines, whose de-
tailed congurations are shown in Table 4. All machines are
connected to Wedge100BF-32X, a programmable switch with
Tono programmable ASIC [17]. For scaling to sixteen meta-
data servers, we deploy a metadata server on each socket of
the server node, using NUMA-local cores, DRAM, and NIC.
Baseline systems. We compare AsyncFS with a widely de-
ployed DFS, Ceph [70], and state-of-the-art academic DFSs
optimized for metadata performance, including IndexFS [55],
InniFS [42] and CFS [69]. We use Ceph release v12.2.13.
IndexFS is compiled from source. We implement InniFS
and CFS, the most recent studies, from scratch as they are
not publicly available. We rst implement InniFS by follow-
ing its paper [42] and implement CFS-KV by replacing In-
niFSs parent-children grouping strategy (i.e., per-directory
hashing) with CFSs parent-children separating strategy (i.e.,
per-le hashing). Note that AsyncFS is also implemented
on the code base of InniFS, thus IndexFS, CFS-KV and
AsyncFS have the same storage and networking framework,
fairly comparing their metadata scheme. We do not compare
with SingularFS [13] and DeltaFS [74]. SingularFS focuses
on boosting per-server performance with novel hardware (i.e.,
persistent memory and RDMA), which is orthogonal to our
work. DeltaFS is designed for HPC jobs, whose semantics are
different from general DFSs.
Implementation details. For IndexFS, CFS-KV and
AsyncFS, they use RocksDB in asynchronous write mode
for storage, and a coroutine-based, non-blocking RPC engine
on DPDK 21.11.2 [49] for networking. Each metadata server
uses four cores if not otherwise specied, and clients use
LibFS to communicate with servers. For Ceph, we deploy
multiple active MDS daemons colocated with OSD daemons.
For AsyncFS, we enable proactive change-log aggregation for
AsyncFS in all experiments, so all directory updates are timely
applied to inodes. With MTU being 1500, each change-log
proactively pushes every 29 change-log entries.
6.2 Overall Performance
6.2.1 Peak Throughput
We rst evaluate the peak throughput of individual operations
and their scalability with regard to the server numbers. To
obtain the peak throughput, we gradually increase the number
of concurrent requests issued by clients until the throughput
no longer increases.
As we discussed in 2.3, existing DFSs make inherent trade-
offs between load balance and operation overhead. Therefore,
their performance varies greatly when evaluated on different
access patterns. We conduct experiments on two different
access patterns, a single-large directory and multiple direc-
tories, which highlight load balance and operation overhead
respectively. IndexFSs throughput on single-large directory
is not included since it consistently terminates with errors.
A single large directory. To highlight the load balance of
the evaluated lesystems, we create a single directory and
perform le operations on 10 million les in the single di-
rectory. From the results shown in Figure 11(a), we have the
following observations.
1) AsyncFSs throughput scales well for double-inode op-
erations including create, delete, mkdir and rmdir, as server
number increases. AsyncFS achieves high scalability for three
reasons. (a) AsyncFSs le-grained partitioning strategy bal-
ances operation loads evenly. (b) The asynchronous metadata
update procotol allows double-inode operations to access only
one server, avoiding corss-server coordination and hiding di-
rectory contention. (c) Change-log recast parallelly merges
conicting directory updates, reconsiling directory contention
before applying directory updates. Note AsyncFSs rmdir
throughput is lower than mkdir, since AsyncFS uses a multi-
cast to notify the invalidation of the directory for rmdir.
2) Although CFS-KV adopts le-grained partitioning strat-
egy, it still hardly scales for create and delete. This is because
operations are serialized on updating the same directory, suf-
fering severe contention. InniFS and CFSs mkdir and rmdir
throughput do not scale for the same reason.
3) For stat, AsyncFS and CFS-KV exhibit linear scaling,
attributed to the effective load balancing of per-le granularity
metadata partitioning. In contrast, InniFS experiences signif-
icant load imbalance due to the assignment of all les within
a large directory to a single server. For statdir, all lesystems
scale linearly as they partition the directories in a balanced
manner. AsyncFSs additional checking for in-ight metadata
aggregations on the directory has negligible overhead.
4) For all evaluated operations, Cephs throughput is low
(below 100 Kops/s), for its heavy software stack and inexible

6.4 Directory Aggregation Overhead
Reading a scattered directory in AsyncFS requires a metadata
aggregation. To evaluate the impact of metadata aggrega-
tion, we repeatedly perform a burst of le create operations
followed by a single statdir in a directory and report the aver-
age latency of the statdir operations. We vary the number of
servers and the number of preceding create operations.
Figure 14(a) shows the statdir latency with various number
of preceding creates on eight servers. The average latency
increases with more creates and nally converges at about
500
s. The convergence is because AsyncFS servers proac-
tively push local change-log entries to the inode when the
entry number reaches the threshold (e.g., 29 in our implemen-
tation), which effectively controls the number of change-log
entries to be applied during aggregation.
Figure 14(b) shows the statdir latency with 100 preceding
creates on different number of servers. The average latency
increases as server increases for two reasons. First, the proba-
bility of les and directories not residing on the same node
increases. Second, the number of change-log entries kept with-
out reaching the per-server threshold increases. Thus, with
more servers, an increased number of change-log entries need
to be applied during aggregation.

exceeding the throughput of a metadata clusters. As a result,
one programmable switch is sufcient to serve a metadata
cluster, while DPDK servers need to partition the namespace
with multiple servers to meet the throughput demand, which
is less nancially effective.

6.6 End-to-End Performance
We evaluate AsyncFS performance on a synthetic workload
with real-world ratio and two real-world trace. We run the
experiments on eight metadata servers and eight datanodes,
and the client issues 256 in-ight requests to pressure the
servers. Table 5 shows the workload composition.
The data center service workload is a synthetic workload
based on the operation ratio captured from Alibabas deployed
PanguFS [42], used to demonstrate AsyncFSs ability to serve
aggregated metadata requests in the data center. Based on this
ratio, we perform 10 million operations in 1024 directories,
with 80% operations in 20% directories to simulate the work-
load skewness. The synthetic workload does not contain data
access since data operation ratio is unknown.
The CV training and thumbnail workloads are repre-
sentative many-small-le scenarios, used to demonstrate
AsyncFSs ability to serve real applications. The CV training
workload is traced from training ALEXNET model [4, 25]
on ImageNet dataset [16], which contains 1.28 million les
(mostly within 256KB) grouped in 1000 directories, and the
trace captures the whole lifecycle of the dataset, including
download, access, and removal. The thumbnail workloads
captures the process of accessing 1 million images (mostly
within 256KB) and creating thumbnails for them. We replay
the trace with data access enabled and disabled respectively.
Figure 17 shows the aggregate throughput of each work-
loads. The CV training and thumbnail workloads are meta-
data intensive since metadata operations account for over
80% of total operations in number and over 50% in runtime.
AsyncFSs signicantly improvement in metadat through-
put leads to a large improvement in end-to-end throughput.
AsyncFS outperforms Ceph, IndexFS and CFS-KV by up to

6.7 Crash Recovery Time
We evaluate the recovery time of AsyncFS in scenarios where
a server or switch failure happens after eight servers create 10
million les in 100 thousand directories. For a server failure,
it takes the crashed server 5.77 seconds to recover
1.25 mil-
lion inodes to its key-value store and
1.25 million not-yet-
applied change-log entries. For a switch failure, it takes 3.82
seconds for all the servers to ush not-yet-applied change-log
entries to restore AsyncFS into a consistent state after the
switch reboot. Note that the server recovery time is propor-
tional to the number of operations to recover, which can be
largely optimized by checkpointing.
7 Related Work
Metadata partitioning. Early DFSs such as GFS [10],
HDFS [62], Farsite [8] and QFS [46] manage all metadata in
a single metadata server. For modern applications with many
small les and massive concurrent metadata access, the single
metadata server become a capacity and performace bottle-
neck. More recent DFSs partition namespace over multiple
metadata servers to scale out.
Some DFSs partition the directory tree in subtree granu-
larity, such as AFS [15] and Ceph [70]. While subtree par-
tition preserves metadata locality, is prone to load imbal-
ance [59, 68]. Some other DFSs adopt per-directory partition,
such as BeeGFS [12], IndexFS [48, 53, 55], HopsFS [44],
Tectonic [47], and InniFS [42]. Since they still group les
inodes with parent directories, they also suffer load imbalance
when operations are intensively performed in a few directories.
CFS [69] adopts per-le partitioning, which achieves good
load balance but suffers cross-server coordination overhead
for double-inode operations.
Previous DFSs have to trade off between load balance and
operation overhead in partition granularity. Unlike previous
DFSs, AsyncFS achieves good load balance by partitioning
in per-le granularity while hiding cross-server coordination
overhead with asynchronous metadata updates. In this way,
AsyncFS achieves the best of both worlds.
Directory contention mitigation. Filesystems are known
to be vulnerable to directory contention for its hierarchi-
cal namespace, and some DFSs explore to mitigate it. Lo-
coFS [35] relaxes POSIX semantics to avoid updating di-
rectory metadata for double-inode operations. DeltaFS [74]
does not provide globally shared namespace but ask clients
to explicitly manage synchronization scope, reducing con-
tention domain. CFS [69] requires cross-server coordination
for double-inode operations while using ordered updates and
database primitive to prune critical section scope for direc-
tory updates. SingularFS [13] stores metadata on persistent
memory on a single server, and update directories with atomic
instruction to reduce contention. AsyncFS provides classical
POSIX-compliant global namespace and not relying on persis-
tent memory. AsyncFSs change-log recast parallelly merges
directory updates, eliminating the single-point serialization
for directory updates, and can be combined with previous
techniques to scale performance in different dimensions.
Distributed lesystems on novel harware. A series of
DFSs adopt novel hardware to boost performance. Octo-
12
pus [41], Orion [71], Assise [3], and SingularFS [13] adopt
persistent memory and RDMA to speed up, and LineFS [24]
adopts SmartNIC for ofoading. Our work is orthogonal to
them as we focus on partitioning strategy for scaling out.
In-network acceleration. The emerging programmable
switch inspires a series of in-network distributed systems, in-
cluding key-value cache [9,21,22,28,33,36,38,40,60,63,76],
in-network computation [14, 26, 37, 39, 57, 58], distributed
memory [27, 67], distributed lock [72, 73], consensus and
concurrency control [5, 6, 23, 31, 32, 64, 75], and schedul-
ing [52, 65]. AsyncFSs in-network structure is similar to that
of Harmonia [75].s However, Harmonia targets in-network
conict detection for fast key-value store replication, while
AsyncFS adopts in-network state tracking for zero-cost asyn-
chronous DFS operations, whose contexts and insights are
different. To our knowledge, AsyncFS is the rst to introduce
in-network optimization to distributed lesystems.
8 Conclusion
This paper proposes AsyncFS, a distributed metadata service
with asynchronous metadata updates to break the trade-off
between operation efciency and load balancing. AsyncFS
co-designs with a programmable switch to efciently trace
directory states in the network, and adopts change-log recast
to alleviate contention over directory metadata. Evaluation
shows that AsyncFS outperforms state-of-the-art systems and
achieves high throughput, low latency, and stable performance
under burst workloads.
